ressions of both aesthetic and experiential transcolonial black politics across the Caribbean world, including Hispaniola, Louisiana and the Gulf South, Jamaica, and Cuba. Johnson examines the lives and work of figures as diverse as armed black soldiers and privateers, female performers, and newspaper editors to argue for the existence of "competing inter-Americanisms" as she uncovers the struggle for unity amidst the realities of class, territorial, and linguistic diversity. These stories move beyond a consideration of the well-documented anxiety insurgent blacks occasioned in slaveholding systems to refocus attention on the wide variety of strategic alliances they generated in their quests for freedom, equality and profit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBlack peoplexMigrationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aBlack peoplezCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlack peoplezGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxMigrationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityzGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aBlackszCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlackszGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  a19th century history.  aafrican american demographics.  aafrican american studies.  ablack history.  ablack oppression.  abooks for history lovers.  acaribbean literature.  acivil rights.  adiscussion books.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  afrench culture.  afrench history.  afrench politics.  ahaitian history.  ahaitian revolution.  ahardships of minorities.  ahistory and politics.